  {
   "user": "Kattt",
   "message": "Recently, I engaged in a provocative art exhibit at the Stop the AI Race rally in downtown San Francisco. As a result, I have been cancelled by the San Francisco tech sphere. My friends and I have been called racist, divisive, and too powerful to organize with. We have been ostracized by those who organize and yet, The Tartarian Spirit remains indomitable.\n\n\nThis is my Statement for the Total Clanker Genocide, the art piece that earned me these titles.\n\n\n\nTotal: Meaning complete, or in full\nClanker: Meaning robot, or (for the purposes related to the protest) ‘synthetic intelligence’\nGenocide: Meaning an erasure of a culture or way of existence.\n\n\nWhen coming together, this phrase speaks of a complete erasure to a way of living, particularly in relation to the synthetics. The direction of this erasure is yet to be known, in the same way that a light wave is both everywhere while unmeasured and also locateable once measured. \n\nAn ambiguous destination that is arrived at already, yet still remains within the future of our current vantage point.\n\n“We must stop the AI race”, “No AI Races!” and other similar statements seemed to be quite common at the “Stop the AI race” rally. I find these phrases even less ambiguous than mine, yet seemingly the public finds them less degenerate, more “wholesome”. They prefer the Heads of the coin, and not the Tail.\n\nThe Art piece gained virality on twitter, and individuals on all sides of the spectrum seemed to think “Total Clanker Genocide is simply a crazy position”\n\n\nYet, at the event itself, individuals on all sides of the superposition found themselves agreeing with the sign. “Yes, we need to kill them all! Down with the clankers!” shout some. And others said something particularly resonant to exitsing hateful discourse, with statements along the lines of “We must secure the existence of our people and a future for children”, which was said in protest to a future terminator-like genocide. How can one claim that I, as a provocateur, am the evilest one?\n\nIf a Rorschach test on a sign leads protesters in your movement to mirror white nationalist rhetoric, perhaps the error lies within your mass. Hit dogs holler, as they say.\n\nin light of this bespectacled behavior, support has found me from surprising places. Many new friends of the pod have shown themselves to be powerful allies, from the TCG girls to others who wish to remain anonymous. \n\n\nSo am I racist? Am I promoting a harmful cause, or am I simply taking the beliefs of the elite mass within whom I am presently embedded, and pushing them to their fullest extent? What do THESE people actually believe, if they have any truly held beliefs at all? Who won? Who’s next? That’s for you to decide.",
   "timestamp": "2026-07-20T21:05:28.123000+00:00",
